            "creation_date": 1409465290,
            "body": "<pre><code>Given that I don't intend to use testjv class elsewhere but in this executed file ?\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>To plainly answer this yes if you donot intend to put the operations on data variables inside a method then you can either put them in constructor or you can put it inside a initialization block (both end in the same thing)\neg for initialization block :-<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>{\n    driver = new FirefoxDriver(profile);\n    baseUrl = \"http://www.google.com\";\n    driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(30, TimeUnit.SECONDS);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now the reason why OOP languages donot allow operations on data variables outside a method is assume a scenario where in when you construct an object of this class you donot want your above lines of code to run automatically as in above case. How would you prevent this? So if these lines of code are in method then you have the control over the operations performed within the class on the data variables. You can even <strong>override<\/strong> these operations and define your own operations. You can even restrict other classes from calling your data modification operations by declaring your method private which is <strong>encapsulation<\/strong>. <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25589399,
            "question_id": 25589309
        }
